<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Mr Chris Terrell (CYS 0032)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Chris Terrell (CYS 0032)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">EXECUTIVE </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">SUMMARY:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Personal background, summary of experience and typical cycle use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Experienced cyclist in several towns and cities in UK, daily commuting and shopping, mostly 'utility' cycling, some recreational cycling and touring.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Outline of local conditions fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">r cycling.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wolverhampton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has some cycling infrastructure but this is fragmented, often poorly maintained and designed and sometimes dangerous.  Cycling in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wolverhampton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is mostly a hazardous activity and practical, safe routes to work and shops are hard to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> find and involve frustrating detours. Signage is poor and inconsistent so routes are hard to find without local knowledge. There appears to be a general indifference to the idea of making it safe and easy to use cycles for daily, practical purposes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">afe do I feel, cycling in UK towns and cities?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Generally unsafe and on the defensive.  I have had several near misses that could have resulted in fatal or serious injuries.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What could be done by central and local government?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Short list of suggestions separ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ated between the two.  Generally, central government should set the lead in creating a national aim to make cycling safe and an easy, practical, realistic choice of transport for normal people. Some national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">standardisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> based on evidence of what works </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">well and involvement of active cyclists in design would be desirable. Legislative changes and appropriate funding will facilitate this. Local government should take a local lead and ensure planning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prioritises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> needs of cyclists and pedestrians in traffic i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nfrastructure design.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do we need segregation?  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Not always total but, in the present conditions and with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prevailing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> attitudes and laws, it is probably a necessary stage and in some road sections it is definitely safer, healthier and a lot more pleasant. Goo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d cycle-paths should also be more convenient to use than the route for vehicles.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Other suggestions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Helmets are over-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emphasised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and often irrelevant. Suggestions for a compulsory cycle element to driving test.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; page-break-before:always"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1. Personal background, summary of experienc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e and typical cycle use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am submitting this evidence in an individual capacity.  I am White, British, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">53</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> years of age and have lived here since 2009.  My main job is as a Technician in a school. I am also a freelance outdoor activity instructor and have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">previously run many outdoor development and training courses concerned with risk assessment.  I would describe myself as an experienced cyclist.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am a member of a social cycling group in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wolverhampton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (Wolves BUG) and a local campaign group (Wolves on W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heels).  I am a member of the CTC.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am also an experienced driver of cars (since 1980) and minibuses (since 1988</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) ,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> plus trailers, and have a motorcycle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">licence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I have lived and cycled in Portsmouth, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Chichester</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Plymouth, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Oswestry</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Haslemere</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (Surrey), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">erdyfi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tywyn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Gwynedd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).  I have also some (very pleasant) recent experience of cycling in the Netherlands.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">My main cycling use is for travelling to work, shopping and visiting friends.  I also use my bike for some recreation, day trips in the surroundi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng area and occasional touring trips further afield, when I make use of trains to get me over the longest distances (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: South Wales, Scotland).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When cycling I make an effort to be easily visible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,  ride</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assertively on the road, claiming my lane and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">signall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and obeying the highway code.  I obey traffic lights, including those for pelican crossings. If I am compelled by dangerous alternatives to ride on a pavement, I am mindful of pedestrians and others and reduce my speed accordingly, stopping and waiting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if necessary.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. Do I feel that cycling is safe in British towns and cities?</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Overall, no.  It always feels like a risky activity, more than it used to be.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many junctions and roundabouts are particularly hazardous, with all vehicles travelling too fast </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to allow any leeway for slower road users – even other motor vehicles. Where any provision for cyclists is made, it is frequently inconvenient or potentially dangerous or ambiguous or a combination of these.  From a car driver's perspective, the inconsiste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ncy of signage and of cycle infrastructure makes for an ambiguous and confusing situation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many of the cycle lanes and paths seem to exist on the easiest parts of routes and often run out in confusing, inconvenient and sometimes dangerous ways at junctions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and narrow road sections (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Willenhall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Road under the railway bridge).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Impatient and aggressive driving, especially from car drivers, is a common factor to contend with.  There appears to be a sense of impunity among many car drivers, given the apparent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rarity of any meaningful or appropriate consequences for bad driving and even for causing serious injury or death to a cyclist (recent cases reflect this,  CTC's Road Justice campaign highlights some of these).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Most cycle infrastructure appears to be an af</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">terthought, tacked onto a planning process that seems to design around the needs of motor vehicles before people and usually lacking any sense of a network of routes that lead where people actually need to go. Roundabouts are often a particularly hazardous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> part of a journey, due to the amount of space and speed of traffic; even riding assertively is a challenge.  </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Outline of local conditions for cycling.</span></li><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I live in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wolverhampton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and commute Monday to Friday by bike to my main work at a Secondary School in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">illenhall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a distance of 5 miles. The quickest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and most efficient route for me is via main roads to cross the City centre and continue on main roads to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Willenhall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is some segregated cycle infrastructure that follows this route and which I use regula</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rly, there are also usable but poorly-maintained canal towpaths that provide a roughly parallel route.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some sections of the cycle infrastructure here are good but overall it is fragmented, poorly-conceived and fails to form a coherent network of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> practica</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> alternative routes to the main roads.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some sections of the cycle routes are, in my </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">judgement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (and that of others) dangerous and I am left with no practical alternative but to ride, with due care, on pavements through those sections to complete my journ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ey safely; I have had several near misses involving cars and buses on these parts of the road and now take the safer option.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I find in general that I cannot avoid cycling through busy to heavy traffic during commuting journeys without making excessive deto</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urs which would make the journey too long.  Shopping trips are no less hazardous and remain inconvenient to do by bike, especially once laden.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Personal security and safety on the canal towpaths varies with the time of day and weather.  There are sections</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the towpaths that I avoid in the evening due to the evidence of anti-social loiterers.  Broken glass is a regular hazard to both the bike and anybody unfortunate enough to fall there.  These factors reduce the usefulness of the towpaths as safe alterna</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tives to the roads on some routes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The towpaths are also generally poorly-maintained, with a lot of rough and muddy sections that are both uncomfortable and hazardous to use.  In snowy and icy weather, they become dangerous to ride on and I have to stay on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the roads or drive.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Similarly, the cycle-paths are not cleared of snow and ice and become hazardous to unusable in winter conditions, especially after a lot of people have compacted the snow into lumpy ice with feet and mountain-bike wheels.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where a cycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lane is provided on some of the roads, it is often blocked by parked cars, against whom no enforcement action ever appears to be taken.  Other cycle lanes are frequently short and stop altogether at junctions and other stretches where they are most needed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Tettenhall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Road has examples of this).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">So far, my experience of drivers' </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> towards me while cycling has been mostly reasonable, however I have been subject to some abuse and dangerously careless driving and have had several near-misses involving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">buses passing too close and cars emerging from junctions without the drivers looking – these would have been serious to fatal for me had I not spotted the danger in time.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is common to see drivers using mobile phones and to notice strong smells of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cannabis from cars passing me, which further adds to my mistrust of drivers' ability to respond properly to other road users. I see no evidence of any attempts by Police to take enforcement action against either of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">behaviours</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How safe do I feel, cyc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ling in UK towns and cities?</span></li><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Generally unsafe and on the defensive.  I have had several near misses that could have resulted in fatal or serious injuries.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By contrast, cycling recently in the Netherlands, I was able to feel relaxed about cycling at any t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ime of day.  My hosts and their children (around 13 years old) all used bikes in the day and evening routinely.  Only racing cyclists wear helmets and there is no need to put on layers of high-visibility clothing.  Lights are fitted to bikes anyway and the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> many varieties of bicycle used for moving all sorts of stuff are impressive (see '</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bakfiets</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">' and variants).</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What could be done by central and local government?</span></li><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Generally, central government should set the lead in creating a national aim and demonstrate pol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">itical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will  to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> make cycling safe and an easy, practical, realistic choice of transport for normal people. Promotion of non-sporting elite cycling is needed, as there is a prevailing image of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lycra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-clad and helmeted athletes as the archetypal 'cyclist', or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> negative but similar stereotypes, which I believe alienate 'ordinary' people and make cycling seem a specialist and elite activity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The approach taken by the Dutch government in transforming attitudes, and the UK government in tackling smoking in pubs, sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould serve as models for what can be done.  Cycling needs to return to being regarded as a normal and safe mode of transport and the benefits promoted.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">standardisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> based on evidence of what works well and active involvement of cyclists in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> infrastructure design would be desirable. Legislative changes and appropriate funding will facilitate this.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A combination of legal changes – the 'presumed liability' model – and rigorous enforcement of existing laws is needed so that cyclists feel protect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed by the law. At present I do not feel confident that I would receive justice when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I  read</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of drivers receiving very lenient penalties for intimidating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, causing serious injury or even death, if they are even prosecuted at all.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More public inform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ation to remind all road users of key points of the highway code and traffic laws needs to be broadcast, in addition to the seasonal 'drink driving' adverts.  Cyclists also need to be reminded to use lights and to obey traffic lights.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Enforcement of traffi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c light laws and on 20mph speed limits is needed; I have been told that local police here are unwilling to enforce the 20mph limits.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cycle training needs promoting and funding.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local government should take a local lead and ensure planning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prioritises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> nee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ds of cyclists and pedestrians in traffic infrastructure design.  These groups of people should be involved in the design process, not just at the initial consultation stages.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do we need segregation?  </span></li><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I am against compulsory segregation, not least because</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it could reinforce the attitude that bikes shouldn't be on the road.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In urban areas, in the present conditions and with prevailing attitudes and laws, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> segregated cycle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">infrastructure  is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> probably a necessary stage and in some road sections it is def</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">initely safer, healthier and a lot more pleasant.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Good cycle-paths should also be more direct and convenient to use than the route for vehicles.</span></li></ol><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Other suggestions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is too much emphasis on wearing helmets. In the falls that I have had, a helmet made n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o difference and might even have given me a neck injury by increasing the whiplash on my neck as my head bounced off the road! I do tend to wear one in traffic on the 'just in case' basis, but most of the injuries I hear of are to legs and backs.  Helmets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should not be made </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">compulsory,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> instead, we should make safer conditions for cycling.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I suggest that there should also be a compulsory cycling element in the driving test, in traffic and on the roads, so that all drivers have some experience of traffic from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the most vulnerable perspective.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 51.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Alternatively, people wishing to take a driving test should have to show that they have recently completed practical cycle training.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>